{"id":"1109.6055","submitter":"Joao Magueijo","authors":"Joao Magueijo","title":"Neutrino oscillations and superluminal propagation, in OPERA or\n  otherwise","comments":"Comment added on consistency with SN1987A, within the proposed\n  models. References added. Minor style changes","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ph astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We digress on the implications of recent claims of superluminal neutrino\npropagation. No matter how we turn it around such behaviour is very odd and\nsits uncomfortably even within \"far-fetched\" theories. In the context of\nnon-linear realizations of the Lorentz group (where superluminal misbehaviour\nis run of the mill) one has to accept rather contrived constructions to predict\nsuperluminal properties for the neutrino. The simplest explanation is to\nrequire that at least one of the mass states be tachyonic. We show that due to\nneutrino mixing, the flavor energy does not suffer from the usual runaway\npathologies of tachyons. For non-tachyonic mass states the theories become more\nspeculative. A neutrino specific dispersion relation is exhibited, rendering\nthe amplitude of the effect reasonable for a standard Planck energy. This uses\nthe fact that the beam energy is close to the geometrical average of the\nneutrino and Planck mass; or, seen in another way, the beam energy is\nunexceptional but its gamma factor is very large. A dispersion relation\ncrossing over from a low energy bradyonic branch to a high energy tachyonic one\nis also considered. We comment on consistency with SN 1987A within these\nmodels.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 27 Sep 2011 22:28:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 6 Oct 2011 13:05:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-10-07"}
{"id":"1109.6056","submitter":"Tomoki Ohsawa","authors":"Melvin Leok, Tomoki Ohsawa and Diana Sosa","title":"Hamilton-Jacobi Theory for Degenerate Lagrangian Systems with Holonomic\n  and Nonholonomic Constraints","comments":"44 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"Journal of Mathematical Physics 53, 072905 (2012)","doi":"10.1063/1.4736733","report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.MP math.SG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We extend Hamilton-Jacobi theory to Lagrange-Dirac (or implicit Lagrangian)\nsystems, a generalized formulation of Lagrangian mechanics that can incorporate\ndegenerate Lagrangians as well as holonomic and nonholonomic constraints. We\nrefer to the generalized Hamilton-Jacobi equation as the Dirac-Hamilton-Jacobi\nequation. For non-degenerate Lagrangian systems with nonholonomic constraints,\nthe theory specializes to the recently developed nonholonomic Hamilton-Jacobi\ntheory. We are particularly interested in applications to a certain class of\ndegenerate nonholonomic Lagrangian systems with symmetries, which we refer to\nas weakly degenerate Chaplygin systems, that arise as simplified models of\nnonholonomic mechanical systems; these systems are shown to reduce to\nnon-degenerate almost Hamiltonian systems, i.e., generalized Hamiltonian\nsystems defined with non-closed two-forms. Accordingly, the\nDirac-Hamilton-Jacobi equation reduces to a variant of the nonholonomic\nHamilton-Jacobi equation associated with the reduced system. We illustrate\nthrough a few examples how the Dirac-Hamilton-Jacobi equation can be used to\nexactly integrate the equations of motion.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 27 Sep 2011 22:38:29 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 12 Sep 2012 16:57:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-09-13"}
